This is a file of a single occurrence of a vocalization recorded at Bukit Sarang Conservation Area, Sarawak on June 13 2017. This is from a Wildlife Acoustics SM2+ recorder that we deployed at the sight, so no visual observations were made. The actual recording began at 0556 and this sound happened about 47 minutes into the recording.  

In this clipped version, the sound starts about 5 seconds in and ranges in frequency from 840-2095 Hz.  I am not certain that this is even a bird.  

Any leads would be much appreciated!

loc: eBird hotspot: Bang Kachao--Sri Nakhon Khuean Khan Park in Bangkok
rmk:
Recorded with my ZOOM H% Handy Recorder. High Pass Filter with Audacity applied

Bangkok's Green lung - I walk in the bushes and for the second time I flush Pink-necked pigeons from the tree sitting 2 meter above me. Impossible to see in the foliage. I ID the birds when they land in a tree across the canal.

Second time and I try to take pictures and I discover one Stork-billed Kingfisher among the pigeons.

Sitting in a tree making this noise I have never heard before. So not sure it was the Kingfisher. The bird dive with a final sound. From behind me another is coming and landing and make the same noise maybe the other bird I could hear very weak when the one in the tree make the noise.

On the picture it looks like the Stork-billed Kingfisher is making the sound

[Picture 1](http://www.aladdin.st/bird-watching/thailand/1705.jpg)

Learned that this sound is the Stork-billed Kingfishers song
